WEBVTT

00:03.102 --> 00:08.948
I had the students do this scenario. I had a

00:08.968 --> 00:16.396
gentleman that was a little bit strange, but he had 
been a corps commander at one time. And he comes in

00:17.337 --> 00:22.062
wearing a saber, and I'm thinking he's going to 
really give us something. He pulls the saber out.

00:24.144 --> 00:29.370
He's running around the classroom with that 
saber, and I'm saying, is he going to stab

00:24.144 --> 00:29.370
somebody? He got someone fired up in his 
presentation. And I'm thinking, do I stop this or

00:32.650 --> 00:35.613
what do I do? That was one of the most disconcerting 
things that ever happened to me. Later it was kind

00:39.676 --> 00:48.784
of funny, but at the time I'm thinking, he was so 
pumped up and fired up, he was jabbing at this, he'd

00:39.676 --> 00:48.784
say the Senate does this or the state does this. It 
was sort of an anti-government kind of

00:49.345 --> 00:55.350
presentation, even though he was supposed to be 
successful in those kinds of things. I think he'd

00:55.710 --> 00:58.973
probably just gone through a divorce and the 
courts had ripped him out. That was a I've often

01:01.473 --> 01:08.364
thought about, and that taught me a lesson about 
what a person can bring into a class and what

01:01.473 --> 01:08.364
they're going to do in a presentation. I've had 
some fun times, too, when I'll have scenarios. One

01:17.237 --> 01:22.185
time I said, all right, you've got to be creative 
with your scenario. Well, here they come. My class

01:23.787 --> 01:25.229
is right down the hall. Here they come carrying a 
guy in on a gurney. Covered up. all this equipment

01:30.481 --> 01:32.103
hanging off of him. Well, they had frozen him in 
time. So he sets up with a sheet on his head, you

01:36.247 --> 01:39.991
know, all white like a dead man. They pull the sheet 
down and push a few buttons, you know, and he rubs

01:40.292 --> 01:50.123
the stuff off his face, and then he goes into his, 
you know, what's happened to the world since he was

01:40.292 --> 01:50.123
frozen.

01:52.045 --> 01:54.908
That was one of the great ones, I think. What 
about...

02:01.025 --> 02:08.518
Oh,

02:01.025 --> 02:08.518
you know, we hear all kinds of stories about 
excuses given. I, you know, I've never really had

02:10.000 --> 02:17.172
any that come to mind that were absurd. I have 
students who are coming, they can't make it

02:17.493 --> 02:25.446
because the school board president called them, 
they couldn't come the last second, or... I'm new

02:25.814 --> 02:29.401
dog it eat my homework kind of stuff. I haven't had 
much of that those kinds of things at this level. No

02:33.490 --> 02:34.252
excuses. I try early on and say that you're gonna 
miss a class. Professionals will have to do that.

02:40.044 --> 02:41.246
Just let me know beforehand. I want you to bring a 
tape recorder to one of your friends the week

02:41.306 --> 02:44.633
before. Don't expect notes to do the job. I want you 
to tape what goes on in class. And they've really

02:49.185 --> 02:51.907
been good at that for the last 20 some odd years. So 
unless I'm totally naive, I have not had much

02:51.967 --> 03:05.420
problem with even worrying about excuses.

